{"id":"1106.2751","submitter":"Eric Tesse","authors":"Eric Tesse","title":"A formal theory of experimentation and its applications to quantum\n  theory","comments":"63 Pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  While it is widely acknowledged that quantum theory is strange, and that the\nworld view it implies is elusive, there is considerably less consensus as to\nwhy this is the case. This article will explore the possibility that the theory\nmay be opaque because the mathematical language it employs is inarticulate. To\naddress this possibility, three interconnected mathematical theories will be\ndeveloped, each specifically designed to handle aspects of quantum theory's\nsubject matter. The first will describe dynamic systems in terms that are\ngeneral enough to be applicable to any kind dynamics, including both classical\nand quantum. That description will then be used to construct a theory of\nexperiments, with the aim of understanding what types of experiments scientific\nmethodology allows. Finally, the theory of experiments will found a theory of\nexperimental probabilities applicable to any collection of experiments, so long\nas their probabilities are internally consistent. The resulting over-arching\nmathematical language will then be applied to quantum theory. In the initial\napplication, it will be used to explain the core nature and structure of\nquantum measurement and probability. Following that, it will be used to explore\nquantum theory's models. Like any theory written in a mathematical language,\nquantum theory derives its meaning from its class of models. To understand the\nclass quantum models, two models of central importance will be described. The\nfirst will be a conceptually simple construction that follows almost\nimmediately from the above theory of dynamics. It fully satisfies both quantum\ntheory and the above mentioned theory of experimentation; additionally, its\nmacroscopic objects obey classical mechanics. The second will utilize a minimal\namount of mathematical structure to satisfy the same conditions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 11 Jun 2011 16:10:42 GMT"},{"version":"v10","created":"Mon, 4 Jun 2018 18:46:05 GMT"},{"version":"v11","created":"Thu, 20 Sep 2018 20:24:04 GMT"},{"version":"v12","created":"Thu, 24 Jan 2019 17:30:33 GMT"},{"version":"v13","created":"Thu, 30 Jul 2020 16:30:05 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 16 Dec 2011 12:24:40 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 23 Feb 2012 17:37:43 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Sat, 25 Feb 2012 13:20:23 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Thu, 29 Sep 2016 19:48:13 GMT"},{"version":"v6","created":"Tue, 18 Oct 2016 15:40:19 GMT"},{"version":"v7","created":"Fri, 4 Nov 2016 00:09:25 GMT"},{"version":"v8","created":"Fri, 16 Dec 2016 15:49:24 GMT"},{"version":"v9","created":"Thu, 31 May 2018 16:58:50 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-07-31"}
